      <section xml:id="sec-sets-functions"><title>Useful tools on sets and functions</title>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-sets"><title>Properties of Sets</title>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-1.1"><title>Distributive laws</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                 <m>A ‚à© (‚à™_Œ± B_Œ±) = ‚à™_Œ±(A ‚à© B_Œ±)</m> and <m>A ‚à™ (‚à©_Œ± B_Œ±) = ‚à©_Œ±(A ‚à™ B_Œ±)</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-1.2"><title>De Morgan's laws</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                 <m>A - (‚à™_Œ± B_Œ±) = ‚à©_Œ±(A - B_Œ±)</m> and <m>A - (‚à©_Œ± B_Œ±) = ‚à™_Œ±(A - B_Œ±)</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <p>
            Template to prove two sets are equal
          </p>

          <definition xml:id="def-1.3"><title>Power Set</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                The <em>power set</em> <m>ùí´(S)</m> of a set <m>S</m> is the set of all subsets of <m>S</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <p>
            Discussion of standard mathematical conventions for notation
            Notation for indices: <m>i,j,k,m,n</m> for finite or countably many indices, <m>Œ±,Œ≤,...</m> for arbitrarily many indices.
            Notation for sets, elements of sets, and sets of sets: Small letters <m>a,b,c,p,q,x,y,z</m> for elements of sets, capital letters <m>A,B,C,X,Y,Z</m> for sets, calligraphic capital letters <m>‚Ñ¨,ùíû,ùíØ,ùí∞</m> for collections of sets.
          </p>

        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-functions"><title>Properties of functions</title>

          <definition xml:id="def-1.6">
            <statement>
              <p>
                For a function <m>f: G ‚Üí H</m>, the set <m>G</m> is the <em>domain</em>, the set <m>H</m> is the <em>codomain</em>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <p>
            Template to define a function
          </p>

          <p>
            Template to prove two functions are equal
          </p>

          <definition xml:id="def-1.7">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A function <m>f: G ‚Üí H</m> is <em>well-defined</em> if whenever <m>g,g' ‚àà G</m> and <m>g = g'</m>, then <m>f(g) = f(g')</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <remark>
            <p>
              All functions are well-defined.
            </p>
          </remark>

          <definition xml:id="def-1.8">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>f: X ‚Üí Y</m> be a function.
                The function <m>f</m> is <em>one-to-one</em> (also called an <em>injection</em> and denoted <m>f: X ‚Ü™ Y</m>) if whenever <m>x,x' ‚àà X</m> and <m>f(x) = f(x')</m> then <m>x = x'</m>.
                The function <m>f</m> is <em>onto</em> (also called a <em>surjection</em> and denoted <m>f: X ‚Ü† Y</m>) if for every <m>y</m> in <m>Y</m>, there is an <m>x</m> in <m>X</m> with <m>f(x) = y</m>.
                The function <m>f</m> is a <em>bijection</em> if <m>f</m> is both one-to-one and onto.
                The function <m>f</m> is <em>invertible</em> if there is a function <m>g:Y ‚Üí X</m> such that <m>f ‚àò g = 1_Y</m> and <m>g ‚àò f = 1_X</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-1.9">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>a: G ‚Üí H, b: H ‚Üí K</m>, and <m>c: K ‚Üí L</m> be functions. Then:
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are one-to-one then ba is one-to-one.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>ba</m> is one-to-one then a is one-to-one.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are onto then <m>ba</m> is onto.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>ba</m> is onto then <m>b</m> is onto.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>a</m> is a bijection if and only if <m>a</m> is invertible.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <example>
            <p></p>
          </example>

          <definition xml:id="def-1.10">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>f: X ‚Üí Y</m> be a function.
                The <em>image</em> of a subset <m>A</m> of <m>X</m> is <m>f(A) := \{f(a) | a ‚àà A\}</m>.
                The <em>preimage</em> of a subset <m>B</m> of <m>Y</m> is <m>f\inv(B) := \{g | g ‚àà X and f(g) ‚àà B\}</m>.
                The <em>image</em> of <m>f</m> is <m>f(X)</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <example>
            <p></p>
          </example>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-pan"><title>PAN = <q>Preimages are nice</q></title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>f: X ‚Üí Y</m>, <m>E ‚äÜ E' ‚äÜ Y</m>, and <m>E_Œ± ‚äÜ Y</m> for all <m>Œ±</m>, then 
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>f\inv(E) ‚äÜ f\inv(E')</m>. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>f\inv(‚à™_Œ± EŒ±) = ‚à™_Œ±f\inv(E_Œ±)</m>. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>f\inv(‚à©Œ± E_Œ±) = ‚à©_Œ±f\inv(E_Œ±)</m>. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>f\inv(E' - E) = f\inv(E') - f\inv(E)</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-iasn"><title>IASN = <q>Images are sometimes nice</q></title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>f: X ‚Üí Y, C ‚äÜ C' ‚äÜ X</m>, and <m>CŒ± ‚äÜ X for all Œ±</m>, then 
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>f(C) ‚äÜ f(C')</m>. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>f(‚à™Œ± CŒ±) = ‚à™Œ± f(CŒ±)</m>. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>f(‚à©Œ± CŒ±) ‚äÜ ‚à©Œ± f(CŒ±)</m>. If moreover <m>f</m> is injective, then <m>f(‚à©Œ± CŒ±) = ‚à©Œ± f(CŒ±)</m>. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>f(C' - C) ‚äá f(C') - f(C)</m>. If moreover f is injective, then <m>f(C' - C) = f(C') - f(C)</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-1.13">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>f: X ‚Üí Y</m>. 
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>A ‚äÜ X</m>, then <m>A ‚äÜ f\inv(f(A))</m>; if moreover <m>f</m> is injective then <m>A = f\inv(f(A))</m>. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>B ‚äÜ Y</m> then <m>f(f\inv(B)) ‚äÜ B</m>; if moreover <m>f</m> is surjective then <m>f(f\inv(B)) = B</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-constructions"><title>Constructions of new sets from old ones, and the associated functions</title>

          <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-subsets"><title>Subsets</title>

            <definition xml:id="def-1.15">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>A</m> be a set. A <em>subset</em> of <m>A</m> is a set of some (possibly none, possibly all, possibly neither) of the elements of <m>A</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <definition xml:id="def-1.16">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>B ‚äÜ A</m>. The <em>inclusion map</em> is the function <m>i:B ‚Üí A</m> defined by <m>i(b) = b</m> for all <m>b ‚àà B</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <proposition xml:id="prop-1.17">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  If <m>B ‚äÜ A</m> and <m>i:B ‚Üí A</m> is the inclusion, then <m>i</m> is an injection.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </proposition>

          </subsubsection>

          <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-products"><title>Product sets</title>

            <definition xml:id="def-1.20">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>A, B</m>, and <m>A_Œ±</m> for all <m>Œ± ‚àà J</m> be sets. The <em>Cartesian product</em> <m>A √ó B := \{(a,b) | a ‚àà A, b ‚àà B\} and ‚àèŒ± ‚àà J A_Œ± := \{(a_Œ±)_{Œ± ‚àà J} | a_Œ± ‚àà A_Œ±\}</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <definition xml:id="def-1.21">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>A_Œ±</m> for all <m>Œ± ‚àà J</m> be sets and let <m>Œ≤</m> in <m>J</m>. The <em>projection map</em> <m>p_Œ≤: ‚àè_{Œ± ‚àà J} A_Œ± ‚Üí A_Œ≤</m> is defined by <m>p_Œ≤((a_Œ±)_{Œ± ‚àà J}) = a_Œ≤ for all (a_Œ±)_{Œ± ‚àà J} ‚àà ‚àè_{Œ± ‚àà J} A_Œ±</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <definition xml:id="def-1.22">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>A_Œ±</m> for all <m>Œ± ‚àà J</m> be sets, let <m>Œ≤ ‚àà J</m>, and for each <m>Œ± ‚àà J - \{Œ≤\}</m>, let <m>b_Œ± ‚àà A_Œ±</m>. The associated <em>product inclusion map</em> <m>i_Œ≤: A_Œ≤ ‚Üí ‚àè_{Œ± ‚àà J} A_Œ±</m> is defined for each <m>a ‚àà A_Œ≤</m> by <m>i_Œ≤(a) := (a_Œ±)_{Œ± ‚àà J}</m>, where <m>a_Œ≤ := a</m> and <m>a_Œ± := b_Œ± for all Œ± ‚àà J - \{Œ≤\}</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <theorem xml:id="thm-1.23">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  <ol>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        Projection maps are surjections. 
                      </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                      <p>
                        Product inclusion maps are injections.
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ol>
                </p>
              </statement>
            </theorem>

            <lemma xml:id="lem-1.24">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  If <m>A ‚äÜ G</m> and <m>B ‚äÜ H</m>, then <m>A √ó B ‚äÜ G √ó H</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </lemma>

            <axiom xml:id="axiom-choice">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Axiom of Choice: If <m>AŒ± ‚â† ‚àÖ</m> for all <m>Œ± ‚àà J</m>, then <m>‚àèŒ± ‚àà J AŒ± ‚â† ‚àÖ</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </axiom>
            
          </subsubsection>

          <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-quotients"><title>Quotient sets and equivalence relations</title>

            <definition xml:id="def-1.27">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  An <em>equivalence relation</em> <m>‚àº</m> on a set <m>X</m> is a subset <m>S</m> of <m>X √ó X</m> (where <m>(a,b) ‚àà S</m> is written <m>a ‚àº b</m>) that satisfies the following for all <m>a,b,c</m> in <m>X</m>: 
                  <ol>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        <m>a ‚àº a</m> (reflexive),
                      </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                      <p>
                        <m>a ‚àº b</m> implies <m>b ‚àº a</m> (symmetric), and 
                      </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                      <p>
                        <m>a ‚àº b</m> and <m>b ‚àº c</m> implies <m>a ‚àº c</m> (transitive).
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ol>
                  The <em>equivalence class</em> of an element <m>a</m> of <m>X</m> is <m>[a] := \{b | b ‚àº a\}</m>.
                  The notation <m>X/‚àº</m> denotes the set of equivalence classes, also called the <em>quotient</em> of <m>X</m> with respect to <m>‚àº</m>.
                  The function <m>q:X ‚Üí X/‚àº</m> defined by <m>q(p) := [p]</m> for all <m>p ‚àà X</m> is called the <em>equivalence map</em>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <definition xml:id="def-1.28">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  A <em>partition</em> of a set <m>X</m> is a collection of nonempty disjoint subsets of <m>X</m> whose union is <m>X</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <proposition xml:id="prop-1.29">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>X</m> be a set. 
                  <ol>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        If <m>‚àº</m> is an equivalence relation on <m>G</m>, then <m>X/‚àº</m> is a partition of <m>X</m>. 
                      </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                      <p>
                        If <m>ùíû</m> is a partition of <m>X</m>, and <m>T = \{(x,y) ‚àà X √ó X | x,y are in the same element of ùíû\}</m>, then <m>T</m> is an equivalence relation on <m>X</m>.
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ol>
                </p>
              </statement>
            </proposition>

            <example>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  
                </p>
              </statement>
            </example>

            <theorem xml:id="thm-1.30">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>f: X ‚Üí Y</m> be a function, and let <m>‚àº = \{(p,p') ‚àà X √ó X | f(p) = f(p')\}</m>. Then <m>‚àº</m> is an equivalence relation on <m>X</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </theorem>

            <theorem xml:id="thm-1.31"><title>FBT = Function Building Theorem for quotient sets</title>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>‚àº</m> be an equivalence relation on a set <m>X</m>, and let <m>f: X ‚Üí Y</m> be a function satisfying the property that whenever <m>x,x' ‚àà X</m> and <m>x ‚àº x'</m> then <m>f(x) = f(x')</m>. Then:
                  <ol>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        There is a well-defined function <m>g:X/‚àº ‚Üí Y</m> defined by <m>g([x]) = f(x)</m> for all <m>[x]</m> in <m>X/‚àº</m>; that is, <m>g ‚àò q = f</m>, where <m>q</m> is the equivalence map.
                      </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                      <p>
                        If <m>f</m> is onto, then <m>g</m> is onto.
                      </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                      <p>
                        If <m>f</m> also satisfies the property that whenever <m>x,x' ‚àà X</m> and <m>f(x) = f(x')</m> then <m>x ‚àº x'</m>, then <m>g</m> is one-to-one.
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ol>
                </p>
              </statement>
            </theorem>

            <p>
              Template for proving a well-defined function with domain <m>X/‚àº</m>.
            </p>

            <example>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  
                </p>
              </statement>
            </example>

            <definition xml:id="def-1.32">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>X</m> be a set and let <m>S</m> be a subset of <m>X √ó X</m>. The <em>equivalence relation on <m>X</m> generated by</em> <m>S</m> is the intersection of all of the equivalence relations on <m>X</m> that contain <m>S</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>
            
          </subsubsection>
          
        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-cardinality"><title>Cardinality</title>

          <definition xml:id="def-1.34">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A set <m>X</m> is <em>finite</em> if there is a bijection <m>X ‚Üí \{1,...,n\}</m> for some natural number <m>n</m>, or <m>X</m> is empty. In this case the number <m>n</m> is called the <em>cardinality</em> of <m>X</m>.
                A set <m>X</m> is <em>infinite</em> if <m>X</m> is not finite. A set <m>X</m> is <em>countable</em> if there is an injection <m>X ‚Ü™ ‚Ñï</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-1.35">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>X</m> be a set.
                (1) The following are equivalent: 
                  (1a) <m>X</m> is finite. 
                  (1b) There is an onto function <m>\{1,...,n\} ‚Ü† X</m> for some <m>n ‚àà ‚Ñï</m>. 
                  (1c) There is a one-to-one function <m>X ‚Ü™ \{1,...,n\}</m> for some <m>n ‚àà ‚Ñï</m>.
                (2) The following are equivalent: 
                  (2a) <m>X</m> is infinite. 
                  (2b) There is an onto function <m>X ‚Ü† ‚Ñï</m>. 
                  (2c) There is a one-to-one function <m>‚Ñï ‚Ü™ X</m>.
                (3) The following are equivalent: 
                  (3a) <m>X</m> is countable. 
                  (3b) There is an onto function <m>‚Ñï ‚Üí X</m>. 
                  (3c) There is an injection <m>X ‚Ü™ ‚Ñï</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-1.36">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The class of finite sets is closed under: subsets, intersections, finite unions, and finite products.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The class of countable sets is closed under: subsets, intersections, countable unions, and finite products.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

