    <chapter xml:id="ch-spaces"><title>Topological Spaces and Continuous Functions</title>

      <section xml:id="sec-topology"><title>Topology and continuity</title>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-topology"><title>Topology</title>
          
          <definition xml:id="def-2.1">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A topology on a set <m>X</m> is a collection <m>ùíØ</m> of subsets of <m>X</m> satisfying: 
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>‚àÖ</m> and <m>X</m> are elements of <m>ùíØ</m>; 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      whenever <m>A_Œ±</m> is in <m>ùíØ</m> for all <m>Œ±</m>, then <m>‚à™_Œ± A_Œ±</m> is in <m>ùíØ</m>; and 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      whenever <m>A_1,...,A_n</m> are in <m>ùíØ</m>, then <m>‚à©_{i=1}^n A_i</m> is in <m>ùíØ</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <definition xml:id="def-2.2">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A topological space is a set <m>X</m> together with a topology <m>ùíØ</m> on <m>X</m>, often denoted <m>(X,ùíØ)</m>. The elements of <m>X</m> are called points in <m>X</m>, and the elements of <m>ùíØ</m> are called open sets in <m>X</m> or open sets relative to <m>X</m> or open sets rel <m>X</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>
          
          <example xml:id="def-2.6">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Examples of topologies and topological spaces:
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Indiscrete topology on a set <m>X: ùíØ_{ind} := \{‚àÖ, X\}</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Discrete topology on a set <m>X: ùíØ+{dis} := \{U | U ‚äÜ X\} = ùí´(X) =</m> the set of all subsets of <m>X</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Euclidean topology on <m>‚Ñù^n: ùíØ_{Eucl} := \{U ‚äÜ ‚Ñù | \text{for all} p ‚àà U \text{there is an} r &gt; 0 \text{and} q ‚àà ‚Ñù^n \text{such that} p ‚àà B(q,r) ‚äÜ U \}</m>, where <m>B(q,r) = B_n(q,r) := \{x ‚àà ‚Ñù^n | d_{Eucl}(q,x) &lt; r\}</m> is the ball of radius <m>r</m> centered at q (and <m>d_Eucl</m> is Euclidean distance).
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
