        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-continuoty"><title>Continuity</title>

          <p>
            Motivation: Unraveling the <m>Œµ-Œ¥</m> definition of continuous in Euclidean space to an equivalent definition on open sets.
          </p>

          <definition xml:id="def-2.20">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> be topological spaces, and let <m>f: X ‚Üí Y</m> be a function. The function <m>f</m> is continuous if and only if for every open set <m>U</m> in <m>Y</m>, the preimage <m>f\inv(U)</m> is open in <m>X</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <example>
            <p>
              Examples
            </p>
          </example>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-2.21">
            <statement>
              <p>
                (CC0) 
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Let <m>c</m> be a real number. The function <m>f:‚Ñù ‚Üí ‚Ñù</m> defined by <m>f(r) := cr</m> for all <m>r ‚àà ‚Ñù</m> is continuous. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The functions from <m>‚Ñù^2</m> to <m>‚Ñù</m> defined by addition, subtraction, and multiplication are continuous. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The function <m>g:‚Ñù √ó (‚Ñù - \{0\}) ‚Üí ‚Ñù</m> defined by <m>g(x,y) := x/y</m> is continuous. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      A uniform limit of continuous functions from <m>‚Ñù</m> to <m>‚Ñù</m> is continuous; hence sine and cosine are continuous.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-2.22">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      (CC1) If <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> are topological spaces and <m>f:X ‚Üí Y</m> is a constant function, then <m>f</m> is continuous. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      (CC2) If <m>f: X ‚Üí Y</m> and <m>g: Y ‚Üí Z</m> are continuous, then the composition <m>g ‚àò f: X ‚Üí Z</m> is continuous.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-2.23">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>(X,ùíØX)</m> and <m>(Y,ùíØY)</m> be topological spaces and let <m>f: X ‚Üí Y</m>. The function <m>f</m> is continuous iff for all <m>V ‚àà ùíØ_Y</m> and <m>f(x) ‚àà V</m>, there exist <m>U ‚àà ùíØ_X</m> with <m>x ‚àà U</m> and <m>f(U) ‚äÜ V</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <definition xml:id="def-2.25">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> be topological spaces. A function <m>f: X ‚Üí Y</m> is a homeomorphism if <m>f</m> is a continuous bijection and <m>f\inv</m> is also continuous. The spaces <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> are called homeomorphic, or topologically equivalent, if there is a homeomorphism from <m>X</m> to <m>Y</m>; in symbols this is written <m>X ‚âÖ Y</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-2.26">
            <statement>
              <p>
                "Homeomorphic" is an equivalence relation on topological spaces.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <example>
            <p>
              Examples
            </p>
          </example>

          <paragraphs><title>Big picture:</title>

            <p>
              Euclidean, spherical and hyperbolic metric spaces of the same dimension are homeomorphic. <m>E^2 ‚âÖ H^2 ‚âÖ S^2 - (0,0,1)</m>.
            </p>

            <definition xml:id="def-2.28">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  The Homeomorphism Problem asks: Is there a computer algorithm that, upon input of two topological spaces <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m>, can determine whether or not <m>X ‚âÖ Y</m>?
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <p>
              (Backing up a step: How do you input a space into a computer?!)
            </p>
            
          </paragraphs>

        </subsection>
        
        <subsection xml:id="subsec-bases"><title>Bases</title>

          <definition xml:id="def-2.30">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A basis on a set <m>X</m> is a collection <m>‚Ñ¨</m> of subsets of <m>X</m> satisfying: 
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      For each <m>p</m> in <m>X</m> there is an <m>N_p</m> in <m>‚Ñ¨</m> such that<m> p ‚àà N_p</m>, and 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      whenever <m>N_1,N_2</m> are in <m>‚Ñ¨</m> and <m>p</m> is an element of <m>N1 ‚à© N2</m>, then there is an <m>N_3</m> in <m>‚Ñ¨</m> such that <m>p ‚àà N_3 ‚äÜ N_1 ‚à© N_2</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <definition xml:id="def-2.31">
            <statement>
              <p>
                The topology generated by a basis <m>‚Ñ¨</m> is <m>ùíØ(‚Ñ¨) := \{U ‚äÜ X | for all p in U there is an N in ‚Ñ¨ such that p ‚àà N ‚äÜ U\}</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <lemma xml:id="lem-2.32">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>‚Ñ¨</m> is a basis on <m>X</m>, then <m>ùíØ(‚Ñ¨)</m> is a topology on <m>X</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>ùíØ'</m> is a topology on <m>X</m>, then <m>ùíØ'</m> is also a basis on <m>X</m>, and <m>ùíØ(ùíØ') = ùíØ'</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </lemma>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-2.33">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>‚Ñ¨</m> is a basis on <m>X</m> and <m>U ‚äÜ X</m>, then <m>U</m> is in <m>ùíØ(‚Ñ¨)</m> if and only if <m>U</m> is a union of elements of <m>‚Ñ¨</m>. That is, <m>ùíØ(‚Ñ¨) = \{ ‚à™Œ± BŒ± | BŒ± ‚àà ‚Ñ¨ for all Œ±\}</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <example xml:id="def-2.36">
            <p>
              The Euclidean basis on <m>‚Ñù^n</m> is <m>‚Ñ¨_{Eucl} := \{ B_n(q,r) | q ‚àà ‚Ñù^n and r &gt; 0\}</m>.
            </p>
          </example>

          <lemma xml:id="lem-2.37">
            <statement>
              <p>
               <m>ùíØ(‚Ñ¨Eucl) = ùíØEucl</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </lemma>

          <definition xml:id="def-2.39">
            <statement>
              <p>
                The lower limit topology on the set <m>‚Ñù</m> is the topology <m>ùíØll := ùíØ(‚Ñ¨ll)</m> generated by the basis <m>‚Ñ¨ll := \{[a,b) | a,b ‚àà ‚Ñù, a &lt; b\}</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-2.40">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>‚Ñ¨Y</m> be a basis on a set <m>Y</m>. A function <m>f: (X,ùíØX) ‚Üí (Y,ùíØ(‚Ñ¨Y))</m> is continuous if and only if for every basis element <m>N ‚àà ‚Ñ¨Y</m>, the preimage <m>f\inv(N)</m> is open in <m>X</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-2.42">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>‚Ñ¨</m> and <m>‚Ñ¨'</m> be bases on a set <m>X</m>. Then <m>ùíØ(‚Ñ¨) ‚äÜ ùíØ(‚Ñ¨')</m> iff for all <m>N</m> in <m>‚Ñ¨</m> and <m>x</m> in <m>N</m>, there is an <m>N'</m> in <m>‚Ñ¨'</m> with <m>x ‚àà N' ‚äÜ N</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>
          
          <theorem xml:id="thm-2.44">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A subbasis on a set <m>X</m> is a collection <m>ùíÆ</m> of subsets of <m>X</m> satisfying <m>‚à™_{U ‚àà ùíÆ} U = X</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-2.45">
            <statement>
              <p>
                The basis generated by a subbasis ùíÆ is ‚Ñ¨(ùíÆ) := \{‚à©i=1n Ui | n ‚àà ‚Ñï and Ui ‚àà ùíÆ for all i\}. The topology generated by a subbasis ùíÆ is ùíØ(ùíÆ) := ùíØ(‚Ñ¨(ùíÆ)).
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-2.46">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let ùíÆY be a subbasis on a set Y.
                (a) 
                The basis ‚Ñ¨(ùíÆY) generated by the subbasis ùíÆY is a basis, and hence the topology ùíØ(ùíÆY) generated by the subbasis ùíÆY is a topology.
                (b) 
                A function f: (X,ùíØX) ‚Üí (Y,ùíØ(ùíÆY)) is continuous if and only if for every subbasis element V ‚àà ùíÆY, the preimage f-1(V) is open in X.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

        </subsection>

      </section>

      <section xml:id="sec-constructions"><title>Constructing new spaces and continuous functions from old ones</title>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-subspaces"><title>Subspaces</title>

          <definition xml:id="def-2.50">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let X be a topological space and let A be a subset of X. The subspace topology on A is ùíØsub := \{U ‚à© A | U is an open set in X\}. The set A with the subspace topology is called a subspace of X. An element V of the subspace topology on A is called open in A or open set relative to A or open rel A.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <remark>
            <p>
              (a) 
              "Open in A" does not mean open and contained in A. 
              (b) 
              In mathematical writing, always specify "open in __", never write just "open".
            </p>
          </remark>

          <proposition xml:id="prop-2.51">
            <statement>
              <p>
                The subspace topology is a topology.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-2.54">
            <statement>
              <p>
                (CC3) If A is a subspace of X, then the inclusion map i:A ‚Üí X is continuous.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <example>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Examples
              </p>
            </statement>
          </example>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-2.56">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If A is a subspace of B and B is a subspace of C then A is a subspace of C.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <proposition xml:id="prop-2.57">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Given a topological space X with topology ùíØ(‚Ñ¨) generated by a basis ‚Ñ¨, and given and Y ‚äÜ X, the subspace topology on Y equals the topology generated by the basis ‚Ñ¨sub = \{ B ‚à© Y | B ‚àà ‚Ñ¨ \}.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>

          <definition xml:id="def-2.59">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let X and Y be sets, let A be a subset of X, let Z be a set containing Y, and let f:X ‚Üí Y be a function. The restriction of f to the domain A is the function f|A:A ‚Üí Y defined by f|A(a) := f(a) for all a ‚àà A. The extension of f to the codomain Z is f|Z:X ‚Üí Z defined by f|Z(p) := f(p) for all p ‚àà X. If B is a subset of Y containing the image f(X) of f, then the restriction of f to the codomain B is the function f|B:X ‚Üí B defined by f|B(p) := f(p) for all p ‚àà X.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-2.60">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Restrictions and extensions of continuous functions are continuous. That is: Let X and Y be topological spaces, let A be a subspace of X, and let B be a subspace of Y. (CC4) The inclusion i: A ‚Üí X is continuous. (CC5) If f: X ‚Üí Y is continuous, then f|A: A ‚Üí Y is continuous. (CC6) If f: X ‚Üí Y is continuous and f(X) ‚äÜ B, then f|B: X ‚Üí B is continuous. (CC7) If f: X ‚Üí B is continuous then f|Y: X ‚Üí Y is continuous.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-2.62">
            <statement>
              <p>
                (CC8) Let X be a topological space and suppose that X = ‚à™Œ± UŒ± with each UŒ± open in X. Let each UŒ± have the subspace topology from X. If f: X ‚Üí Y is a function satisfying f|UŒ±: UŒ± ‚Üí Y is continuous for all Œ±, then f is continuous.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <definition xml:id="def-2.64">
            <statement>
              <p>
                An imbedding of a topological space X in a topological space Y is a map f:X ‚Üí Y such that the restriction f|f(X):X ‚Üí f(X) of f to the codomain f(X), with the subspace topology on f(X) from Y, is a homeomorphism.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <corollary xml:id="cor-2.65">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If A is a subspace of X, then the inclusion map i:A ‚Üí Xis an imbedding.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </corollary>

          <example>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Examples of homeomorphic Euclidean subspaces
              </p>
            </statement>
          </example>
         
        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-product"><title>Product spaces</title>

          <definition xml:id="def-2.70">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let (XŒ±,ùíØŒ±) be a topological space for each index Œ± ‚àà J, and let ‚àèŒ± XŒ± be the Cartesian product of the spaces XŒ±. For each index Œ≤, let pŒ≤: ‚àèŒ± XŒ± ‚Üí XŒ≤ be the projection map.
                (a) 
                The product topology on ‚àèŒ± XŒ± is the topology ùíØprod := ùíØ(ùíÆprod) generated by the product subbasis ùíÆprod := \{ pŒ≤-1(UŒ≤) | Œ≤ ‚àà J and UŒ≤ ‚àà ùíØŒ≤ \}. The set ‚àèŒ± XŒ± with the product topology is called a product space.
                (b) 
                The box topology on ‚àèŒ± XŒ± is the topology ùíØbox := ùíØ(‚Ñ¨box) generated by the box basis ‚Ñ¨box := \{‚àèŒ± UŒ± | UŒ± is open in XŒ± for all indices Œ±\}.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <proposition xml:id="prop-2.71">
            <statement>
              <p>
                (a) 
                The product subbasis is a subbasis. 
                (b) 
                The box basis is a basis. 
                (c) 
                For a collection of spaces (XŒ±,ùíØŒ±) for Œ± ‚àà J, ùíØprod ‚äÜ ùíØbox; and if J is finite then ùíØprod = ùíØbox.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>

          <proposition xml:id="prop-2.73">
            <statement>
              <p>
                For a collection of spaces (XŒ±,ùíØŒ±) the product topology on ‚àè XŒ± equals the product generated by the basis ‚Ñ¨prod = \{ ‚àè BŒ± | BŒ± ‚àà ùíØŒ± for all Œ±, and BŒ± = XŒ± for all but finitely many Œ± \}. (The collection ‚Ñ¨prod is called the product basis.)
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>

          <proposition xml:id="prop-2.75">
            <statement>
              <p>
                (CC9) Let XŒ± be a topological space for each index Œ±, and let ‚àèŒ± XŒ± have the product topology. Then for each index Œ≤, the projection map pŒ≤: ‚àèŒ± XŒ± ‚Üí XŒ≤ is continuous.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>

          <example>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Examples
              </p>
            </statement>
          </example>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-2.78">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let X = ‚Ñùn. Let ùíØEucl be the Euclidean topology on X, and let ùíØprod be the product topology on X induced by the Euclidean topology on each of the ‚Ñù1 factors. Then ùíØEucl = ùíØprod.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-2.80">
            <statement>
              <p>
                (CC10) Let XŒ± be a topological space for each index Œ± in an index set J, and let ‚àèŒ± XŒ± have the product topology. Let Œ≤ ‚àà J, and for each Œ± ‚àà J - \{Œ≤\}, let pŒ± be an (particular choice of) element of XŒ±. Then the associated product inclusion map iŒ≤: XŒ≤ ‚Üí ‚àèŒ± XŒ± is an imbedding.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <definition xml:id="def-2.82">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let A be a set, and for each Œ± in an index set J let XŒ± be a set and let fŒ±:A ‚Üí XŒ±. The product function (fŒ±)Œ± ‚àà J: A ‚Üí ‚àè XŒ± is defined by (fŒ±)Œ± ‚àà J(a) := (fŒ±(a))Œ± ‚àà J for all a ‚àà A.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>
          
          <lemma xml:id="lem-2.83">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let A be a set, and for each Œ± let XŒ± be a set. Then: 
                (a) 
                Each function f: A ‚Üí ‚àè XŒ± is a product function f = (fŒ±)Œ± such that fŒ±: A ‚Üí XŒ± is defined by fŒ± := pŒ± ‚àò f for each index Œ±. 
                (b) 
                Given functions gŒ±:A ‚Üí XŒ± for each Œ± in J, the product function g := (gŒ±)Œ± ‚àà J satisfies gŒ± = pŒ± ‚àò g for all Œ±.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </lemma>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-2.84">
            <statement>
              <p>
                (CC11) Let A be a topological space, and for each index Œ± let XŒ± be a topological space. Let ‚àè XŒ± have the product topology and let f: A ‚Üí ‚àè XŒ±. Then f is continuous if and only if pŒ± ‚àò f is continuous for all Œ±.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-2.87">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let AŒ± be a subspace of a space XŒ± for all Œ±. Let ùíØprod be the product topology on ‚àèŒ± AŒ±. Let ùíØsub be the subspace topology on ‚àèŒ± AŒ± induced by the product topology on ‚àèŒ± XŒ±. Then ùíØprod = ùíØsub.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>
       
        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-quotient-spaces"><title>Quotient = identification spaces</title>

          <definition xml:id="def-2.90">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Def 2.90: 
                Let X be a topological space and let ‚àº be an equivalence relation on X. Let X/‚àº be the set of equivalence classes and let q: X ‚Üí X/‚àº be the equivalence map (defined by q(p) := [p] for all p in X). The quotient topology, or identification topology on X/‚àº induced by ‚àº, is the topology ùíØ‚àº = ùíØquo:= \{U ‚äÜ X/‚àº | q -1(U) is open in X\}. The set X/‚àº together with the quotient topology is called a quotient space of X, and the equivalence map q is called the quotient map induced by ‚àº.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <proposition xml:id="prop-2.92">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Prop 2.92: 
                The quotient topology is a topology.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>

          <proposition xml:id="prop-2.93">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Prop 2.93: 
                (CC12-i) If X/‚àº is a quotient space of X and q: X ‚Üí X/‚àº is the equivalence map (defined by q(p) := [p] for all p in X), then q is a continuous surjection.
                (b) The quotient topology induced by an equivalence relation is the largest topology on the set of equivalence classes for which the equivalence map is continuous.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>

          <definition xml:id="def-2.95">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Def 2.95: 
                Let (X,ùíØX) be a topological space, let Y be a set, and let f:X ‚Üí Y be a surjective function. The quotient topology on Y induced by f is ùíØq := \{V ‚äÜ Y | f-1(V) ‚àà ùíØX\}. If Y has the quotient topology induced by f then f is called a quotient map.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <proposition xml:id="prop-2.97">
            <statement>
              <p>
                The quotient topology induced by a function f is a topology.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>

          <proposition xml:id="prop-2.98">
            <statement>
              <p>
                (CC12-ii) If f is a quotient map, then f is a continuous surjection.
                (b) The quotient topology induced by a map f is the largest topology on the codomain of f for which the map f is continuous.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>

          <proposition xml:id="prop-2.100">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let X be a topological space.
                (a) 
                If ‚àº is an equivalence relation on X, then the quotient topology on X/‚àº induced by ‚àº equals the quotient topology on X/‚àº induced by the equivalence map q:X ‚Üí X/‚àº (defined by q(p) := [p] for all p in X).
                (b) 
                If f:X ‚Üí Y is a surjection, then the quotient space (Y,ùíØf) is homeomorphic to the quotient space (X/‚àº,ùíØ‚àº) induced by the equivalence relation on X defined by x ‚àº x' if and only if f(x) = f(x') for all x,x' ‚àà X; moreover, the homeomorphism g:X/‚àº ‚Üí Y satisfies g ‚àò q = f, where q is the equivalence map.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>

          <example>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Examples
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                
              </p>
            </solution>
          </example>

          <p>
            1-dimensional examples: Quotients of a line segment [0,1]:
          </p>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-2.104">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let X = [0,1] have the Euclidean subspace topology, and let ‚àº be the equivalence relation on X defined by p ‚àº q if and only if either [p=q] or [\{p,q\} = \{0,1\}]. Then the quotient space X/‚àº is isomorphic to S1.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <p>
            2-dimensional (surface) examples: Quotients of the square [0,1] √ó [0,1]:
          </p>

          <definition xml:id="def-2.106">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let X = [0,1] √ó [0,1] have the product topology (where each [0,1] has the Euclidean subspace topology).
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The torus T2 is the quotient space X/‚àº where ‚àº is the equivalence relation on X generated by (r,0) ‚àº (r,1) and (0,s) ‚àº (1,s) for all r,s ‚àà [0,1].
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>

                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The Klein bottle K2 is the quotient space X/‚àº where ‚àº is the equivalence relation on X generated by (r,0) ‚àº (r,1) and (0,s) ‚àº (1,1-s) for all r,s ‚àà [0,1].
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>

                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The Mobius band M2 is the quotient space X/‚àº where ‚àº is the equivalence relation on X generated by (0,s) ‚àº (1,1-s) for all s ‚àà [0,1].
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <definition xml:id="def-2.108">
            <statement>
              <p>
                The projective plane P2 is the quotient space P2 := S2/‚àº where S2 := \{(x,y,z) ‚àà ‚Ñù3 | x2 + y2 + z2 = 1\} is the 2-sphere (with the Euclidean subspace topology) and ‚àº is the equivalence relation generated by (x,y,z) ‚àº (-x,-y,-z) for all (x,y,z) ‚àà S2.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-2.110">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let X = [0,1] √ó [0,1] have the product topology (where each [0,1] has the Euclidean subspace topology).
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The cylinder S1 √ó [0,1] is homeomorphic to the quotient space X/‚àº where ‚àº is the equivalence relation on X generated by (r,0) ‚àº (1,r) for all r ‚àà [0,1].
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The projective plane P2 is homeomorphic to the quotient space X/‚àº where ‚àº is the equivalence relation on X generated by (r,0) ‚àº (1-r,1) and (0,1-s) ‚àº (1,s) for all r,s ‚àà [0,1].
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The 2-sphere S2 is homeomorphic to the quotient space X/‚àº where ‚àº is the equivalence relation on X generated by (r,0) ‚àº (0,r) and (s,1) ‚àº (1,s) for all r,s ‚àà [0,1].
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The torus T2 is homeomorphic to the product space S1 √ó S1 where each S1 has the Euclidean subspace topology.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>
          
          <theorem xml:id="thm-2.120">
            <statement>
              <p>
                (CC13 and CQ1) (CFBT = "Continuous Function Building Theorem for quotient spaces"): 
                Let X and Z be topological spaces, let ‚àº be an equivalence relation on X, let q: X \to X/‚àº be the equivalence map, and let X/‚àº have the quotient topology. Suppose that f: X \to Z is a continuous function that is constant on equivalence classes. Then: 
                (1) 
                The map f induces a continuous function g: X/‚àº \to Z with g ‚àò q = f. 
                (2) 
                If f is onto then g is onto. 
                (2') 
                If f is a quotient map, then g is a quotient map. 
                (3) 
                If [ f(x)=f(x') implies q(x)=q(x') for all x,x' ‚àà X] then g is one-to-one. 
                (4) 
                If f is a quotient map and (3) holds then g is a homeomorphism.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <definition xml:id="def-2.123">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let X and Y be topological spaces. An <em>open map</em> from X to Y is a function f:X ‚Üí Y such that for every open set V in X, the image f(V) is open in Y.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <proposition xml:id="prop-2.124">
            <statement>
              <p>
                (CO1) 
                (a) 
                A composition of open functions is open.
                (b) 
                (CO2) If XŒ± has the topology TŒ± for each Œ± ‚àà J, and ‚àèŒ± ‚àà J XŒ± has the product topology, then the projection map pŒ≤ : (‚àèŒ± ‚àà J XŒ±) ‚Üí XŒ≤ is open.
                (c) 
                If f:X ‚Üí Y is an open function and if B is a subspace of Y satisfying f(X) ‚äÜ B ‚äÜ Y, then f|B is an open map.
                (d) 
                (CO3) A finite product of open maps is open.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-2.126">
            <statement>
              <p>
                (CQ2) If f: X ‚Üí Z is continuous, onto, and open, then f is a quotient map.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <proposition xml:id="prop-2.127">
            <statement>
              <p>
                There exist quotient maps that are not open maps.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>

          <definition xml:id="def-2.130">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A <em>retraction</em> of a topological space X to a subspace A is a continuous function r:X ‚Üí A satisfying r(a) = a for all a ‚àà A.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-2.131">
            <statement>
              <p>
                (CQ3) Every retraction is a quotient map.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <definition xml:id="def-2.134">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let (X,ùíØX) and (Y,ùíØY) be topological spaces with X ‚à© Y = ‚àÖ. The <em>disjoint union topology</em> on X ‚à™ Y is ùíØ‚àê = \{ U ‚à™ V | U ‚àà ùíØX and V ‚àà ùíØY \}.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <definition xml:id="def-2.136">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let X1 and X2 be disjoint topological spaces, let Ai be a subspace of Xi for each i, and let f : A1 ‚Üí A2 be a continuous function. The <em>disjoint union</em> of X1 and X2 glued along f, denoted X1 ‚àêf X2 is defined to be the quotient of the disjoint union space X1 ‚à™ X2 associated to the the smallest equivalence relation ‚àº such that a ‚àº f(a) for all a in A1.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-2.137">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If Ai is a subspace of Xi for i = 1,2 and f : A1 ‚Üí A2 is continuous, then the function g: X2 ‚Üí X1 ‚àêf X2 defined by g(p) := [p] (for all p in X2) is an embedding.
