      <section xml:id="sec-metric"><title>Metrizability</title>

        <definition xml:id="def-3.20">
          <statement>
            <p>
              A metric on a set X is a function d: X √ó X ‚Üí ‚Ñù satisfying the following for all x,y,z ‚àà X: 
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    d(x,y) ‚â• 0, and d(x,y) = 0 if and only if x = y. 
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    d(x,y) = d(y,x). 
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    d(x,z) ‚â§ d(x,y) + d(y,z). 
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
              The pair (X,d) is a metric space, and for any x,y ‚àà X the real number d(x,y) is the distance from x to y.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>

        <definition xml:id="def-3.22">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let d be a metric on a set X. For any p ‚àà X and r ‚àà ‚Ñù with r &gt; 0, the ball of radius r centered at p is Bd(p,r) := {q ‚àà X | d(p,q) &lt; r}.
              The metric basis on X induced by d is the collection ‚Ñ¨d := {Bd(p,r) | p ‚àà X and r &gt; 0}.
              The metric topology on X induced by d is the topology ùíØd := ùíØ(‚Ñ¨d) generated by the metric basis.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>

        <proposition xml:id="prop-3.24">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let (X,d) be a metric space. The metric basis on X is a basis, and hence the metric topology is a topology.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </proposition>

        <theorem xml:id="thm-3.25">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let (X,d) be a metric space, let X have the metric topology, and let X √ó X have the product topology Then the metric function d: X √ó X ‚Üí (‚Ñù,ùíØEucl) is continuous.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </theorem>

        <example>
          <p>
            Examples
          </p>
        </example>

        <definition xml:id="def-3.27">
          <statement>
            <p>
              A topological space (X,ùíØX) is metrizable if there is a metric d on X such that ùíØX = ùíØd (where ùíØd is the metric topology on X induced by d).
