                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If XŒ± is a path-connected space for all Œ±, then the product space ‚àèŒ± XŒ± is path-connected. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If X is a path-connected space and ‚àº is an equivalence relation on X, then the quotient space X/‚àº is path-connected.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <remark>
            <p>
              Path-connectedness is not preserved by subspaces or continuous preimages.
            </p>
          </remark>

          <lemma xml:id="lem-3.83">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let X be a topological space and suppose that X = ‚à™ XŒ± and ‚à© XŒ± ‚â† ‚àÖ. If XŒ± is PC subspace of X for all Œ±, then X is PC.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </lemma>

        </paragraphs>

        <paragraphs><title>Interactions with homeomorphism invariants:</title>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-3.90">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If X is a path-connected space, then X is connected.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <definition xml:id="def-3.93">
            <statement>
              <p>
                The flea and comb space is the subset
                X := {(0,1)} ‚à™ (I √ó {0}) ‚à™ (‚à™n ‚àà ‚Ñï {1/n} √ó I) of ‚Ñù2 with the Euclidean subspace topology. The point (0,1) is the flea and the subspace X - {(0,1)} is the comb.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-3.94">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Connectedness does not imply path-connectedness. In particular, the flea-and-comb space is connected but not path-connected.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-3.96">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A subspace Y of (‚Ñù,ùíØEucl) is path-connected iff Y is either an interval, ray, or ‚Ñù.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>
          
        </paragraphs>

        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-components"><title>Components</title>

          <definition xml:id="def-3.100">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let X be a topological space, and let ‚àºcc be the equivalence relation on X defined by [p ‚àºcc q if and only if there is a connected subspace A of X with p,q ‚àà A]. A connected component of A is an equivalence class for the relation ‚àºcc.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <definition xml:id="def-3.102">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let X be a topological space, and let ‚àºpc be the equivalence relation on X defined by [p ‚àºpc q if and only if there is a path in X from p to q]. A path component of A is an equivalence class for the relation ‚àºpc.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <example>
            <p>
              Examples
            </p>
          </example>

          <lemma xml:id="lem-3.104">
            <statement>
              <p>
                ‚àºcc and ‚àºpc are equivalence relations.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </lemma>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-3.105">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let X be a topological space. Then X is a disjoint union of its connected components. Moreover, each connected component is a disjoint union of path components.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-3.108">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The number (cardinality) of connected components is a homeomorphism invariant. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The number (cardinality) of path components is a homeomorphism invariant.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

        </subsection>     

      </section>

      <section xml:id="sec-compactness"><title>Compactness</title>

        <p>
          Motivation: Characterize spaces for which the Extreme Value Theorem holds.
        </p>

        <definition xml:id="def-3.120">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let X be a topological space. A collection ùíû of subsets of X is said to cover X, or to be a covering of X, if ‚à™C ‚àà ùíû C = X. An open covering of a topological space X is a collection ùíû of open sets in X that covers X.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>

        <definition xml:id="def-3.121">
          <statement>
            <p>
              A topological space X is compact if every open covering of X contains a finite subcollection that also covers X.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>

        <theorem xml:id="thm-3.124"><title>EVT = Extreme Value Theorem</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let X be a compact space, and let f: X ‚Üí (‚Ñù,ùíØEucl) be a continuous function. Then there exist c,d ‚àà X such that for all p ‚àà X, f(c) ‚â§ f(p) ‚â§ f(d).
            </p>
          </statement>
        </theorem>

        <example>
          <p>
            Examples
          </p>
        </example>

        <paragraphs><title>Interactions with constructions and continuous functions:</title>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-3.128">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let A be a subspace of a topological space (X,ùíØX). The space A is compact if and only if for every collection ùíû of open sets in X satisfying A ‚äÜ ‚à™C ‚àà ùíû C, there is a finite subcollection ùíü ‚äÜ ùíû such that A ‚äÜ ‚à™D ‚àà ùíü D.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-3.132">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A continuous image of a compact space is compact. That is, if X,Y are topological spaces, and if X is compact and f: X ‚Üí Y is a continuous surjective function, then Y is compact.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <corollary xml:id="cor-3.133">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Compactness is a homeomorphism invariant.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </corollary>

          <corollary xml:id="cor-3.134">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If X is a compact space and X/‚àº is a quotient space, then X/‚àº is compact.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </corollary>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-3.138">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If A is a subspace of a compact space X and A is a closed subset in X, then A is compact.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-3.139">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Every compact subspace of a Hausdorff space is closed. That is, if Y is a compact subspace of a T2 space X, then Y is a closed subset of X.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <corollary xml:id="cor-3.142">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If Y is a compact subspace of a T2 space X, and p ‚àà X - Y, then there are disjoint open sets U,V in X satisfying p ‚àà U and Y ‚äÜ V.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </corollary>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-3.145">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If X and Y are compact spaces, then the product space X √ó Y is compact. 
                      (a') ("Tychonoff theorem") If XŒ± is a compact space for all Œ±, then the product space ‚àèŒ± XŒ± is compact.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li><title>Tube Lemma</title>
                    <p>
                      If X and Y are spaces, p ‚àà X, Y is compact, and N is an open set in the product space X √ó Y containing {p} √ó Y, then there is an open set W in X such that {p} √ó Y ‚äÜ W √ó Y ‚äÜ N.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <remark>
            <p>
              Compactness is not preserved by non-closed subspaces or continuous preimages.
            </p>
          </remark>

        </paragraphs>

        <theorem xml:id="thm-3.150"><title>VUT = Very Useful Theorem</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              A continuous bijection from a compact space to a Hausdorff space is a homeomorphism.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </theorem>

        <corollary xml:id="cor-3.152"><title>CH-HBT = Compact Hausdorff Homeomorphism Building Theorem</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let X be a compact space, let ‚àº be an equivalence relation on X, and let X/‚àº be the quotient space. If Z is a T2 space and f: X ‚Üí Z is a continuous surjection satisfying [f(p) = f(q) if and only if p ‚àº q] for all p,q ‚àà X, then the function g: X/‚àº ‚Üí Z defined by g([p]) := f(p) for all [p] ‚àà X/‚àº is a homeomorphism.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </corollary>

        <theorem xml:id="thm-3.153"><title>(CQ4)</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              If X is a compact space, Y is a T2 space, and f: X ‚Üí Y is a surjective continuous function, then f is a quotient map.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </theorem>

        <paragraphs><title>Compactness and Euclidean topology:</title>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-3.155">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If a,b ‚àà ‚Ñù with a  &lt;  b, then the interval [a,b], with the subspace topology from (‚Ñù,ùíØEucl), is compact.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <definition xml:id="def-3.157">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let (X,d) be a metric space. The diameter of a nonempty subset Y of X is diam(Y) := sup{d(p,q) | p,q ‚àà Y}. The set Y is bounded if diam(Y) is finite.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-3.158"><title>Heine-Borel Theorem</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let Y be a subspace of (‚Ñùn,ùíØEucl). Then Y is compact iff Y is a closed and bounded subset of ‚Ñùn.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>
            
        </paragraphs>

        <proposition xml:id="prop-3.160">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    If ‚âà is the smallest equivalence relation on I such that 0 ‚âà 1, then I/‚âà ‚âÖ S1, with a homeomorphism that maps the equivalence class [s] to the point ( cos(2 œÄ s) , sin(2 œÄ s) ) for all s ‚àà I.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    If ‚àº is the smallest equivalence relation on I √ó I such that (s,1) ‚àº (1,1) for all s ‚àà I and (0,t) ‚àº (1,1) ‚àº (1,t) for all t ‚àà I, then (I √ó I)/‚àº ‚âÖ D2, with a homeomorphism that maps the equivalence class [(1,1)] to the point (1,0) and maps [(s,0)] to (cos(2œÄs),sin(2œÄs)) for all s ‚àà I.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </proposition>

        <theorem xml:id="thm-3.162">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let X be a topological space, let ‚àº be an equivalence relation on X, and let q:X ‚Üí X/‚àº be the quotient map. Let I = [0,1] have the Euclidean subspace topology.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    The function q':X √ó I ‚Üí (X/‚àº) √ó I defined by q'(p,t) := (q(p),t) for all (p,t) ‚àà X √ó I is a quotient map.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    The relation ‚âà on X √ó I defined by [(p,t) ‚âà (p',t') if and only if p ‚àº p' and t = t' for all (p,t),(p',t') ‚àà X √ó I] is an equivalence relation on X √ó I.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    The function h:(X √ó I)/‚âà ‚Üí (X/‚àº) √ó I defined by h([(p,t)]) := [(q(p),t)] for all [(p,t)] ‚àà (X √ó I)/‚âà is a homeomorphism.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </theorem>

        <theorem xml:id="thm-3.166"><title>Lebesgue Number Lemma</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              If X is a compact metrizable space and ùíû is an open covering of X, then there is a real number s &gt; 0 such that whenever A is a subset of X with diameter  &lt;  s, then there is an open set U in ùíû with A ‚äÜ U.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </theorem>

      </section>

      <section xml:id="sec-separation"><title>Separation and countable basis properties</title>

        <introduction>
          <p>
            Motivation: Characterize metrizability (in particular for compact spaces) in terms of properties defined via open sets.
          </p>
        </introduction>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-countable-basis"><title>Countable Basis</title>

          <definition xml:id="def-3.170">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A space (X,ùíØX) has a countable basis if the topology ùíØX is generated by a basis that is a countable set.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-3.171">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A countable basis is a homeomorphism invariant.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-3.172">
            <statement>
              <p>
                The property of having a topology generated by a countable basis is preserved by subspaces and countable products.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <example>
            <p>
              Examples
            </p>
          </example>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-3.174">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If (X,ùíØX) is a compact and metrizable space, then ùíØX is generated by a countable basis. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Metrizability does not imply a countable basis.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>
          
        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-separation"><title>Separation properties</title>

          <definition xml:id="def-3.180">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let X be a topological space.
                X is T1 if for any points a,b ‚àà X with a ‚â† b, there are open sets U,V in X with a ‚àà U, b ‚àâ U, a ‚àâ V, and b ‚àà V.
                X is T2, or Hausdorff, if for any points a,b ‚àà X with a ‚â† b, there are open sets U,V in X with U ‚à© V = ‚àÖ, a ‚àà U, and b ‚àà V.
                X is T3 if X is T1 and for any point a ‚àà X and closed set B in X with a ‚àâ B, there are open sets U,V in X with U ‚à© V = ‚àÖ, a ‚àà U, and B ‚äÜ V.
                X is T4 if X is T1 and for any closed sets A,B in X with A ‚à© B = ‚àÖ, there are open sets U,V in X with U ‚à© V = ‚àÖ, A ‚äÜ U, and B ‚äÜ V.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <remark>
            <p>
              If X is a T1 space, then T3 is also called regular and T4 is also called normal.
            </p>
          </remark>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-3.183">
            <statement>
              <p>
                For each 1 ‚â§ i ‚â§ 4, the property Ti is a homeomorphism invariant.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <proposition xml:id="prop-3.185">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A space X is T1 if and only if all one-points sets are closed in X.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-3.186">
            <statement>
              <p>
                For each 2 ‚â§ i ‚â§ 4, the property Ti implies the property Ti-1, but the converse fails.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <example>
            <p>
              Examples
            </p>
          </example>

          <paragraphs><title>Interactions with constructions</title>

            <theorem xml:id="thm-3.190">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  T2 and T3 are preserved by subspaces and products.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </theorem>

            <remark>
              <p>
                T2 and T3 are not preserved by quotients. T4 is not preserved by subspaces, products, or quotients.
              </p>
            </remark>
            
          </paragraphs>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-3.194">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A space X is T3 iff X is T1 and for all x ‚àà X and open U in X with x ‚àà U, there is an open set V in X with x ‚àà V ‚äÜ ClX(V) ‚äÜ U.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-3.195">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A space X is T4 iff X is T1 and for all closed A and open U in X with A ‚äÜ U, there is an open set V in X with A ‚äÜ V ‚äÜ ClX(V) ‚äÜ U.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>
          
        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-separation-interactions"><title>Interactions among homeomorphism invariants</title>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Metrizable spaces are T4. (The converse is not true.)
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-3.200">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Compact Hausdorff spaces are T4. (The converse is not true.)
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-3.202">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A T3 space with a countable basis is T4.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-3.208"><title>Urysohn's Lemma</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let X be a T1 space. The following are equivalent: 
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      X is T4. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Whenever A and B are disjoint closed subsets of X, there is a continuous function f : X ‚Üí [0,1] such that f(A) = {0} and f(B) = {1}.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-3.210"><title>UMT = Urysohn Metrization Theorem</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                If X is a T3 space with a countable basis, then X is metrizable.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <corollary xml:id="cor-3.212">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let X be compact. The following are equivalent: 
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      X is metrizable. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      X is T2 and has a countable basis.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </corollary>
  
        </subsection>
        
      </section>

    </chapter>

    <chapter xml:id="ch-homotopy"><title>Homotopy</title>

      <section xml:id="sec-homotopy-overview"><title>Overview of algebraic topology</title>

        <p>
          Motivation: Homeomorphism invariants in Chapter 3 are not enough to answer the Homeomorphism Problem, and in particular they cannot show that a sphere is not homeomorphic to a torus.
        </p>

        <p>
          Motivation: Homotopy equivalence (written ‚âÉ) is an equivalence relation that allows deforming/retracting spaces.
        </p>

        <definition xml:id="def-4.1">
          <statement>
            <p>
              The Homotopy Equivalence Problem asks: Is there a computer algorithm that, upon input of two topological spaces X and Y, can determine whether or not X ‚âÉ Y?
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>

        <definition xml:id="def-4.2">
          <statement>
            <p>
              The Classification Problem asks: Is there a computer algorithm that can list all topological spaces up to homeomorphism, or up to homotopy equivalence?
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>

        <remark>
          <p>
            Use homeomorphism invariants to prove X ‚âá Y, and use homotopy invariants to prove X ‚âÑ Y.
          </p>
        </remark>

        <remark>
          <p>
            Motivation: Construct groups associated to topological spaces that, up to isomorphism, are homotopy invariants:
              Homotopy groups of spaces - all groups
              Homology groups of spaces - abelian groups
              Categories and functors
          </p>
        </remark>
       
      </section>

      <section xml:id="sec-retracts"><title>Retracts</title>

        <definition xml:id="def-4.10">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let A be a subspace of a topological space X. The space A is a retract of X if there is a continuous function r: X ‚Üí A satisfying r(a) = a for all a ‚àà A.
              The function r is called a retraction from X to A.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>

        <definition xml:id="def-4.12">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let Y be a subspace of a topological space X. A deformation retraction of X onto Y is a family of maps ft: X ‚Üí X for all t ‚àà I such that:
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    f0 = 1X,
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    f1(X) = Y,
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    ft|Y = 1Y for all t ‚àà I, and
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    the function H: X √ó I ‚Üí X defined by H(p,t) := ft(p), for all p ‚àà X and t ‚àà I, is continuous.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
              The function H is also called a deformation retraction from X to Y.
              The space Y is called a deformation retract of X, written X ‚áù Y.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>

        <lemma xml:id="lem-4.14">
          <statement>
            <p>
              If {ft}t ‚àà I is a deformation retraction from a topological space X onto a subspace Y, then ft: X ‚Üí X is continuous for all t ‚àà I. Moreover, f1 is the composition of a retraction from X to Y with the inclusion map i: Y ‚Ü™ X.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </lemma>

        <definition xml:id="def-4.20">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let X and Y be topological spaces and let f:X ‚Üí Y be a continuous map. Let (X √ó I) ‚àê Y have the disjoint union topology (where X √ó I has the product topology), and let ‚àº be the minimal equivalence relation on (X √ó I) ‚àê Y such that (p,1) ‚àº f(p) for all p ‚àà X. The mapping cylinder of f is the quotient space Xf := ((X √ó I) ‚àê Y)/‚àº.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>

        <theorem xml:id="thm-4.21">
          <statement>
            <p>
              If Xf is the mapping cylinder associated to a continuous function f:X ‚Üí Y, then the functions g:X ‚Üí Xf defined by g(p) := [(p,0)] for all p ‚àà X and h:Y ‚Üí Xf defined by h(y) := [y] for all y ‚àà Y are embeddings.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </theorem>

        <theorem xml:id="thm-4.22">
          <statement>
            <p>
              If X and Y are topological spaces and f:X ‚Üí Y is a continuous map, then Y is homeomorphic to a deformation retract of the mapping cylinder Xf associated to f.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </theorem>

        <definition xml:id="def-4.25">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let X be a topological space and let f:X ‚Üí X be a continuous map. Let X √ó I have the product topology, and let ‚àº be the minimal equivalence relation on X √ó I such that (p,1) ‚àº (f(p),0) for all p ‚àà X. The mapping torus of f is the quotient space Tf := (X √ó I)/‚àº.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>

        <remark>
          <p>
            If X is a topological space and f:X ‚Üí X is a continuous map, then X may not be homeomorphic to a deformation retract of the mapping cylinder Tf associated to f.
          </p>
        </remark>

      </section>
      
      <section xml:id="sec-homotopy-equiv"><title>Homotopy and homotopy equivalence</title>

        <p>
          Motivation: Deformation retraction is not symmetric and so is not an equivalence relation on topological spaces; build a (smallest) equivalence relation that includes deformation retraction.
        </p>

        <definition xml:id="def-4.30">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let X and Y be topological spaces and let g,h: X ‚Üí Y continuous functions. A homotopy from g to h is a family of maps ft: X ‚Üí Y for all t ‚àà I such that
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    f0 = g,
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    f1 = h, and
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    the function H: X √ó I ‚Üí Y defined by H(p,t) := ft(p), for all p ‚àà X and t ‚àà I, is continuous.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
              The function H is also called a homotopy from g to h.
              The function g is said to be homotopic to h, written g ‚âÉ h.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>

        <lemma xml:id="lem-4.31">
          <statement>
            <p>
              If g,h: X ‚Üí Y are continuous functions and {ft}t ‚àà I is a homotopy from g to h, then ft: X ‚Üí X is continuous for all t ‚àà I.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </lemma>

        <lemma xml:id="lem-4.32">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let X and Y be topological spaces. Homotopy is an equivalence relation on the set of functions X ‚Üí Y.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </lemma>

        <proposition xml:id="prop-4.35">
          <statement>
            <p>
              If Y is a subspace of a topological space X and {ft}t ‚àà I is a deformation retraction from X onto Y, then {ft}t ‚àà I is a homotopy from f0 = 1X to f1, and f1 is the composition of a retraction from X to Y with the inclusion map i: Y ‚Ü™ X.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </proposition>

        <example>
          <p>
            Examples
          </p>
        </example>

        <definition xml:id="def-4.37">
          <statement>
            <p>
              If Z is a topological space and f,g: Z ‚Üí (‚Ñùn,ùíØEucl) are continuous functions, then the straight line homotopy from f to g is the function H: Z √ó I ‚Üí ‚Ñùn defined by H(p,t) := (1-t)f(p) + tg(p) for all p ‚àà X and t ‚àà I.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>

        <proposition xml:id="prop-4.38">
          <statement>
            <p>
              If H is straight line homotopy from f to g, then H is a homotopy from f to g.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </proposition>

        <definition xml:id="def-4.40">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let X and Y be topological spaces, let Z be a subspace of X, and let g,h: X ‚Üí Y continuous functions that satisfy g|Z = h|Z. A homotopy from g to h relative to Z is a family of maps ft: X ‚Üí Y for all t ‚àà I such that
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    f0 = g,
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    f1 = h,
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    the function H: X √ó I ‚Üí Y defined by H(p,t) := ft(p), for all p ‚àà X and t ‚àà I, is continuous, and
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    ft|Z = g|Z for all t ‚àà I.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
              The function H is also called a homotopy from g to h relative to Z.
              The function g is said to be homotopic to h relative to Z, written g ‚âÉZ h.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>

        <definition xml:id="def-4.44">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Topological spaces X and Y are homotopy equivalent, written X ‚âÉ Y, if there are continuous functions f:X ‚Üí Y and g:Y ‚Üí X such that f ‚àò g ‚âÉ 1Y and g ‚àò f ‚âÉ 1X.
              The functions f and g are called homotopy equivalences, and each function is a homotopy inverse of the other.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>

        <theorem xml:id="thm-4.45">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Homotopy equivalence is an equivalence relation on topological spaces.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </theorem>

        <lemma xml:id="lem-4.47">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let X and Y be topological spaces. 
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    If X ‚âÖ Y then X ‚âÉ Y. 
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    If f,g: X ‚Üí Y and f = g then f ‚âÉ g. If moreover Z is any subspace of X then f ‚âÉZ g also.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </lemma>

        <definition xml:id="def-4.50">
          <statement>
            <p>
              A property P of topological spaces is a homotopy invariant if whenever X ‚âÉ Y and X has property P, then Y has property P.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>

        <remark>
          <p>
            Use homotopy invariants to prove two spaces are NOT homotopy equivalent.
          </p>
        </remark>

        <theorem xml:id="thm-4.52">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Path-connectedness is a homotopy invariant.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </theorem>

        <proposition xml:id="prop-4.53">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Compactness is not a homotopy invariant.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </proposition>

        <theorem xml:id="thm-4.54">
          <statement>
            <p>
              If Y is a deformation retract of X, then X ‚âÉ Y.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </theorem>

        <theorem xml:id="thm-4.55">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let X and Y be topological spaces. Then X ‚âÉ Y if and only if there is a space Z such that X and Y are both deformation retracts of Z.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </theorem>
        
        <corollary xml:id="cor-4.56">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let ‚âà be the smallest equivalence relation on spaces such that whenever Y is a deformation retract of X then Y ‚âà X. Then X ‚âÉ Z iff X ‚âà Z.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </corollary>

        <definition xml:id="def-4.60">
          <statement>
            <p>
              A space X is contractible if X ‚âÉ P, where P = {*} is the topological space with one point.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>

        <definition xml:id="def-4.62">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let X and Y be topological spaces. A map f:X ‚Üí Y is null homotopic if f is homotopic to a constant function.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>

        <theorem xml:id="thm-4.62">
          <statement>
            <p>
              A space X is contractible iff the identity map 1X on X is nullhomotopic.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </theorem>

        <example>
          <p>
            Examples
          </p>
        </example>
        
      </section>
      
