    <chapter xml:id="ch-fundamental"><title>Fundamental Groups</title>

      <section xml:id="sec-pi1"><title>Definition of œÄ1</title>

        <definition xml:id="def-5.1">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let X be a topological space and let x0 ‚àà X. A loop in X at x0 is a continuous function f:I ‚Üí X with f(0) = f(1) = x0.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>

        <definition xml:id="def-5.3">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Two paths f,g:I ‚Üí X in a space X are path homotopic, written f ‚âÉp g, if there is a continuous function H: I √ó I ‚Üí X such that H(s,0) = f(s) and H(s,1) = g(s) for all s ‚àà I, and H(0,t) = f(0) and H(1,t) = f(1) for all t ‚àà I.
              The map H is called a path homotopy.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>

        <lemma xml:id="lem-5.4">
          <statement>
            <p>
              If X is a topological space, then ‚âÉp is an equivalence relation on the set of paths in X.
            </p>
          </statement>
