                <li>
                  <p>
                    If f(1) = g(0), then their product, written f‚àóg, is the path in X from f(0) to g(1) defined by (f‚àóg)(s) := f(2s) for all s ‚àà [0,1/2] and (f‚àóg)(s) := g(2s-1) for all s ‚àà [1/2,1].
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    The constant path at x0, written cx0, is the path (loop) in X defined by cx0 := x0 for all s ‚àà I.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    The reverse of the path f is the path frev:I ‚Üí X defined by frev(s) := f(1-s) for all s ‚àà I.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>

        <lemma xml:id="lem-5.8">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let f,g,h,k:I ‚Üí X be paths in a space X, and let x0 := f(0) and x1 := f(1).
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    If f ‚âÉp g and h ‚âÉp k, then f‚àóh ‚âÉp g‚àók.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    cx0‚àóf ‚âÉp f ‚âÉp f‚àócx1.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
