      <section xml:id="sec-present"><title>Presenting and decomposing groups</title>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-presentations"><title>Review and presentations</title>

          <p>
            Review of normal subgroups, cosets, quotients, and generators for subgroups and normal subgroups
          </p>

          <definition xml:id="def-5.70">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let A be a set, let A' := {a-1 | a ‚àà A} be a set that bijects to A, let (A ‚à™ A')* be the set of all words written with the letters of A ‚à™ A' (including the empty word, denoted 1), and let ‚àº be the smallest equivalence relation on (A ‚à™ A')* such that xaa-1y ‚àº xy ‚àº xa-1ay for all a ‚àà A and x,y ‚àà (A ‚à™ A')*. The free group on A, denoted F(A), is the quotient set (A ‚à™ A')*/‚àº with the group operation [v][w] := [vw] where vw is the concatenation of the words v and w. In the case that |A| = n, this group is also denoted Fn.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <definition xml:id="def-5.75">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let A be a set and let R be a subset of F(A). The normal subgroup generated by R is \langle R  \rangle^N := {u1r1e1u1-1 ¬∑¬∑¬∑ ukrkekuk-1 | k ‚â• 0, and ri ‚àà R, ei ‚àà {1,-1}, and ui ‚àà F(A) for each 1 ‚â§ i ‚â§ k}.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <definition xml:id="def-5.77">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let A be a set and let R be a subset of F(A). The group presented by the presentation \langle A | R \rangle is the quotient group F(A)/\langle R  \rangle^N. The set A is the set of generators, the set R is the set of relators, and the set of equations {r = 1 | r ‚àà R} is the set of relations of the presentation.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <definition xml:id="def-5.78">
            <statement>
              <p>
                For a set A, R ‚äÜ F(A), and words v,w ‚àà(A ‚à™ A')*, the equation v = w means that v and w are the same word, v =F(A) w means that [v] = [w] in the group F(A), and v =G w means that [v]\langle R  \rangle^N = [w]\langle R  \rangle^N in the group G := \langle A | R  \rangle.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <remark>
            <p>
              The group \langle A | R \rangle is the largest group generated by A satisfying r =G 1 for all r ‚àà R.
            </p>
          </remark>

          <definition xml:id="def-5.80">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A group G is finitely generated if G is a quotient of F(A) for some finite set A, and G is finitely presented if G = \langle A | R \rangle for some finite sets A and R.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <example>
            <p>
              Examples
            </p>
          </example>

          <lemma xml:id="lem-5.83">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If G is a group, then G has a presentation; moreover, G is presented by G = \langle G | ab = (ab) for all a,b ‚àà G  \rangle.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </lemma>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-5.85"><title>HBTP = "Homomorphism Building Theorem for presentations"</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let G = \langle A | R  \rangle, let H be a group, and let f:A ‚Üí H be a function satisfying the property that for all words b1e1 ¬∑¬∑¬∑ bmem ‚àà R (with each bi ‚àà A and ei ‚àà {1,-1}), f(b1)e1 ¬∑¬∑¬∑ f(bm)em =H 1. Then there is a unique group homomorphism h:G ‚Üí H satisfying h(a) = f(a) for all a ‚àà A.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <definition xml:id="def-5.87">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let A be a set, let R ‚äÜ F(A), let b be a letter not in A, let w ‚àà F(A), and let r ‚àà \langle R \rangle^N. The operations \langle A | R \rangle ‚Üî \langle A ‚à™ {b} | R ‚à™ {b = w} \rangle and \langle A | R \rangle ‚Üî \langle A | R ‚à™ {r} \rangle are Tietze transformations.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-5.88">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If \langle A | R \rangle ‚âÖ \langle B | S  \rangle, then there is a finite sequence of Tietze transformations from \langle A | R \rangle to \langle B | S  \rangle.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-decomposing-groups"><title>Building new groups from old -- or decomposing groups</title>

          <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-abelianization"><title>Abelianization</title>

            <definition xml:id="def-5.95">
              <statement>
                <p>
