            <corollary xml:id="cor-5.209">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  If X and Y are PC CW complexes, then X ‚à® Y is a CW complex and œÄ1(X ‚à® Y) ‚âÖ œÄ1(X) ‚àó œÄ1(Y).
                </p>
              </statement>
            </corollary>

            <definition xml:id="def-5.212">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  A topological space X is defined to be locally path-connected, or LPC, if for every point p ‚àà X and every open set U of X containing p, there is an open set V of X such that p ‚àà V ‚äÜ U and (as a subspace of X) V is path-connected.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <corollary xml:id="cor-5.213">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  CW complexes are LPC.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </corollary>

            <definition xml:id="def-5.215">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  A topological space X is simply-connected, or SC, if X is PC and œÄ1(X) = 1.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <definition xml:id="def-5.216">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  A space X is semi-locally simply connected, or SLSC if for each point p of X there is an open set Up of X containing p such that the inclusion map Up ‚Üí X induces the constant homomorphism œÄ1(Up,p) ‚Üí œÄ1(X,p) to the identity element of œÄ1(X,p).
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <corollary xml:id="cor-5.217">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  CW complexes are SLSC.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </corollary>
            
          </paragraphs>

          <paragraphs><title>Interactions with constructions:</title>

            <definition xml:id="def-5.220">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let X be a CW complex. A subcomplex of X is a closed subspace A in X satisfying the property that whenever eŒ± is an open cell of X and eŒ± ‚à© A is nonempty, then ClX(eŒ±) ‚äÜ A.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>

            <theorem xml:id="thm-5.222">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  If A is a subcomplex of a CW complex X, then A is a CW complex.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </theorem>

            <theorem xml:id="thm-5.224">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  If X and Y are compact CW complexes, then X √ó Y is also a compact CW complex.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </theorem>
            
          </paragraphs>
        
        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-fund-cw"><title>Fundamental groups of CW complexes</title>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-5.230">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let X be a 2-dimensional PC CW complex and let p ‚àà X be the basepoint. The inclusion map X(1) ‚Üí X(2) induces a surjective homomorphism of fundamental groups whose kernel is generated by loops based at p in bijection with the 2-cells of X. More precisely: For each face f = eŒ±2 of X define Œ∏Œ±: I ‚Üí X by Œ∏Œ± := iX(1)X ‚àò œÜŒ± ‚àò œâ, where iX(1)X: X(1) ‚Üí X is the inclusion map and œâ:I ‚Üí SŒ±1 is defined by œâ(t) := (cos(2œÄt),sin(2œÄt)) for all t ‚àà I. Let Œ≥Œ±:I ‚Üí X be a path from p to Œ∏Œ±(0), and let wf := Œ≥Œ± ‚àó Œ∏Œ± ‚àó Œ≥Œ±rev. Then œÄ1(X,p) ‚âÖ œÄ1(X(1),p) / \langle{[wf]}\rangle^N.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-5.231">
            <statement>
              <p>
                For any PC CW complex X, œÄ1(X) ‚âÖ œÄ1(X(2)).
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-5.233"><title>Algorithm to present œÄ1(CW)</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let X be a PC CW complex and let p ‚àà X(0) be the basepoint. Let œâ:I ‚Üí SŒ±1 be defined by œâ(t) := (cos(2œÄt),sin(2œÄt)) and let œÅ:I ‚Üí D1 be defined by œÅ(t) := 2t - 1 for all t ‚àà I. Suppose that for each face (2-cell) f = eŒ±2 of X, the map sf: I ‚Üí X defined by sf := iX(1)X ‚àò œÜŒ± ‚àò œâ satisfies sf(0) ‚àà X(0) and sf follows an edge path in X(1). Then a presentation for œÄ1(X,p) can be computed as follows:
                Step 0: Choose a maximal tree T in the 1-skeleton X(1). For each vertex v of X, let tv: I ‚Üí X be the (shortest) path in T from p to v.
                Step 1: For each edge e = eŒ±e1 of X(1) outside of T, let ae be the loop in X at p defined by ae' := tŒ¶Œ±e(-1) ‚àó be ‚àó tŒ¶Œ±e(1)rev, where be := Œ¶Œ±e ‚àò œÅ is the path in X from Œ¶Œ±e(-1) to Œ¶Œ±e(1) that traverses the edge e. Let ae := [ae']. Then œÄ1(X(1),p) = F({ae | e is an edge of X outside of T}).
                Step 2: For each face f = eŒ±f2 of X(2), let rf'' := tsf(0) ‚àó sf ‚àó tsf(1)rev. By inserting and/or deleting path products with paths of the form e ‚àó erev and erev ‚àó e for edges e in T into rf'', create a path rf' that is a path product of paths of the form ae' or (ae')rev for edges e outside of T; that is, [rf'] =œÄ1(X(1),p) rf for some word rf = ae1j1 ¬∑¬∑¬∑ aemjm with m ‚â• 0 and each ji ‚àà {¬± 1}. Then œÄ1(X,p) = œÄ1(X(2),p) = \langle {ae | e is an edge of X outside of T} | {rf = 1 | f is a face of X}  \rangle.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <definition xml:id="def-5.235">
            <statement>
              <p>
                The presentation complex associated to a presentation \langle A | R \rangle of a group G is a CW complex with one vertex v, an edge ea for each a ‚àà A (with attaching maps gluing both endpoints of ea to v), and a face fr for each r ‚àà R with attaching map determined by following the edges according to the word r.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-5.236"><title>"2-Way Street Thm"</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                For every group G, there is a 2-dimensional PC CW complex X with œÄ1(X) ‚âÖ G. Moreover, if \langle A | R \rangle is a presentation of G and Y is the associated presentation complex, then œÄ1(Y) ‚âÖ G.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

