    <chapter xml:id="ch-covering"><title>Covering Spaces</title>

      <section xml:id="sec-liting"><title>Definitions and Lifting</title>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-lift-defs"><title>Definition</title>

          <definition xml:id="def-6.1">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A covering space of a topological space X is a space XÃÉ together with a continuous function p: XÃÉ ‚Üí X satisfying: There is an open covering {UŒ±} of X such that for all Œ± the preimage p-1(UŒ±) is a disjoint union of open sets in XÃÉ, each of which is mapped (by the restriction of p) homeomorphically onto UŒ±. Each set UŒ± is called evenly covered.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <example>
            <p>
              Examples
            </p>
          </example>

        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-lift-thms"><title>Lifting Theorems</title>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-6.3"><title>PPHLT = Path and Path Homotopy Lifting Theorems</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let p: (XÃÉ,xÃÉ0) ‚Üí (X,x0) be a covering space.

                <ul>
                  <li><title>PLT</title>
                    <p>
                      Given a path f: (I,0) ‚Üí (X,x0), there is a unique path fÃÉ: (I,0) ‚Üí (XÃÉ,xÃÉ0) such that p ‚àò fÃÉ = f.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li><title>PHLT</title>
                    <p>
                      Given a path homotopy H: (I √ó I,(0,0)) ‚Üí (X,x0), there is a unique path homotopy HÃÉ: (I √ó I,(0,0)) ‚Üí (XÃÉ,xÃÉ0) such that p ‚àò HÃÉ = H. Moreover, if H is a path homotopy between two paths f,g: (I,0) ‚Üí (X,x0), then HÃÉ is a path homotopy between the "lifts" fÃÉ,gÃÉ: (I,0) ‚Üí (XÃÉ,xÃÉ0) of f,g from the PLT.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-6.4">
            <statement>
              <p>
                (LC+ULP = Lifting Criterion and Unique Lifting Property): Let p: (XÃÉ,xÃÉ0) ‚Üí (X,x0) be a covering space, let Y be a PC and LPC space, and let f: (Y,y0) ‚Üí (X,x0) be continuous.
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If f‚àó(œÄ1(Y,y0)) ‚äÜ p‚àó(œÄ1(XÃÉ,xÃÉ0)), then there is a unique continuous function fÃÉ: (Y,y0) ‚Üí (XÃÉ,xÃÉ0) such that p ‚àò fÃÉ = f.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If f‚àó(œÄ1(Y,y0)) ‚äà p‚àó(œÄ1(XÃÉ,xÃÉ0)), then there does not exist a continuous lift fÃÉ: (Y,y0) ‚Üí (XÃÉ,xÃÉ0) such that p ‚àò fÃÉ = f.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-6.6">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If p: (XÃÉ,xÃÉ0) ‚Üí (X,x0) is a covering space, then the induced homomorphism p‚àó: œÄ1(XÃÉ,xÃÉ0) ‚Üí œÄ1(X,x0) is injective (that is, Ker p‚àó = {1œÄ1(XÃÉ,xÃÉ0)}), and the image satisfies Im p‚àó = p‚àó(œÄ1(XÃÉ,xÃÉ0)) = {[f] ‚àà œÄ1(X,x0) | the lift fÃÉ of f at xÃÉ0 is a loop in XÃÉ}. Consequently, œÄ1(XÃÉ,xÃÉ0) is isomorphic to a subgroup of œÄ1(X,x0).
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-group-apps"><title>Application to group theory</title>

          <corollary xml:id="cor-6.7">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      For all n ‚àà ‚Ñï, the free group Fn is a subgroup of F2. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The free group F(S) on a countably infinite set S is a subgroup of F2.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </corollary>
          
        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-shhets"><title>The number of sheets</title>

          <definition xml:id="def-6.10">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let p: (XÃÉ,xÃÉ0) ‚Üí (X,x0) be a covering space such that X and XÃÉ are PC. The number of sheets of the covering space is |p-1({x0})|.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-6.11"><title>Lifting Correspondence</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let p: (XÃÉ,xÃÉ0) ‚Üí (X,x0) be a covering space such that X and XÃÉ are PC. Then:
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The Lifting Correspondence Function Œ¶: œÄ1(X,x0)/p‚àó(œÄ1(XÃÉ,xÃÉ0)) ‚Üí p-1({x0}) defined by Œ¶(p‚àó(œÄ1(XÃÉ,xÃÉ0))[f]) := fÃÉ(1), where fÃÉ is the unique lift of the loop f to a path in XÃÉ starting at xÃÉ0, is a well-defined bijection.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      For all points x' ‚àà X, |p-1({x'})| = |p-1({x0})| = (the number of sheets of p) = the index of p‚àó(œÄ1(XÃÉ,xÃÉ0)) in œÄ1(X,x0).
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <example>
            <p>
              Examples
            </p>
          </example>
          
        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-lift-int"><title>Interactions with functions and constructions:</title>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-6.18">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If p:XÃÉ ‚Üí X is a covering space, then p is an open map.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-6.20">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let p:XÃÉ ‚Üí X be a covering space. If A is a subspace of X and √É := p-1(A), then the restriction p|A√É:√É ‚Üí A is also a covering space.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-6.21">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let pi:XÃÉi ‚Üí Xi be covering spaces for i ‚àà {1,2}. Then q := (p1 ‚àò proj1,p2 ‚àò proj2) :XÃÉ1 √ó XÃÉ2 ‚Üí X1 √ó X2 [that is, q(s1,s2) := (p1(s1),p2(s2)) for all (s1,s2) ‚àà XÃÉ1 √ó XÃÉ2] is also a covering space.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-lift-inv"><title>Interactions with homeomorphism invariants:</title>

          <corollary xml:id="cor-6.25">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let p:XÃÉ ‚Üí X be a covering space. If X is a CW complex, then XÃÉ is a CW complex. Moreover, p maps open n-cells to open n-cells for all n.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </corollary>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-6.27">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let p:XÃÉ ‚Üí X be a covering space satisfying the property that p-1({s}) is finite and nonempty for all s ‚àà X. The space XÃÉ is compact and T2 if and only if the space X is compact and T2.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>
          
        </subsection>

      </section>

      <section xml:id="sec-actions"><title>Building Covering Spaces Using Group Actions</title>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-csga"><title>Covering space group actions</title>

          <definition xml:id="def-6.40">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Given a group G and a topological space Y, an action of G on Y (or "action of G on Y by homeomorphisms") is a homomorphism œÅ:G ‚Üí Homeo(Y), where Homeo(Y) is the group of homeomorphisms :Y ‚Üí Y with group operation given by composition. For each g ‚àà G and y ‚àà Y, denote g ¬∑ y := (œÅ(g))(y).
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <definition xml:id="def-6.42">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Given an action of a group G on a space Y, let ‚àºG be the equivalence relation on Y defined by [y ‚àºG y' iff there is a g ‚àà G with g ¬∑ y = y'] for all y,y' ‚àà Y. For each y ‚àà Y, the equivalence class [y] = [y]G = G ¬∑ y is called the orbit of y. The quotient space Y/‚àº is called the orbit space of the group action and denoted Y/G.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <definition xml:id="def-6.44">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A covering space action of a group G on a space Y is an action satisfying: For each y ‚àà Y there is an open set Uy in Y containing y such that whenever g,g' ‚àà G and (g ¬∑ Uy) ‚à© (g' ¬∑ Uy) ‚â† ‚àÖ then g = g'.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-6.45">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If G has a covering space action on Y, then: 
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The quotient p:Y ‚Üí Y/G is a covering space. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If Y is PC and LPC and y0 ‚àà Y, then p‚àó(œÄ1(Y,y0)) ‚ä¥ œÄ1(Y/G,[y0]) and G ‚âÖ œÄ1(Y/G,[y0]) / p‚àó(œÄ1(Y,y0)).
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <corollary xml:id="cor-6.46">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If Y is an SC CW complex and G acts on Y with a covering space action, then œÄ1(Y/G) ‚âÖ G.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </corollary>

        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-building-cs"><title>Building SC covering spaces from group presentations</title>

          <definition xml:id="def-6.50">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let \langle A | R \rangle be a presentation of a group G. The Cayley complex of this presentation is the CW complex XÃÉ constructed by: XÃÉ(0) = G. The set of edges is in bijection with G √ó A; for each g ‚àà G and a ‚àà A, the attaching map of the edge eg,a is œÜg,a(-1) = g and œÜg,a(1) = ga. The set of faces is in bijection with G √ó R; for each g ‚àà G and r ‚àà R, the attaching map œÜg,r of the face fg,r satisfies œÜg,r ‚àò œâ := edge path in XÃÉ(1) starting at g labeled by r.
                The 1-skeleton XÃÉ(1) is the Cayley graph of G with respect to A.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-6.52">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let \langle A | R \rangle be a presentation of a group G, let XÃÉ be the Cayley complex, and let X be the presentation complex. Then
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      the action of G on XÃÉ, given by g ¬∑ h := (gh), g ¬∑ eh,a := e(gh),a, and g ¬∑ fh,r := f(gh),r for all h ‚àà G, a‚àà A, and r ‚àà R, is a covering space action;
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      XÃÉ is a SC CW complex (and hence PC, LPC, and SLSC), and hence œÄ1(XÃÉ/G) ‚âÖ G; and 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      XÃÉ/G ‚âÖ X.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <example>
            <p>
              Examples
            </p>
          </example>

        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-existence"><title>Existence of covering spaces</title>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-6.60">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let X be a PC, LPC, SLSC space and x0 ‚àà X. Then:
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      (SC Covering Space Thm): There is a SC covering space p:(XÃÉ,xÃÉ0) ‚Üí (X,x0), and there is covering space group action of G := œÄ1(X,x0) on XÃÉ that induces p; hence (XÃÉ/G,[xÃÉ0]) ‚âÖ (X,x0). Moreover, if X is a CW complex, then XÃÉ is a CW complex, and for each open n-cell œÉ of X there are |G| open n-cells of XÃÉ mapping via p to œÉ such that the action of each g ‚àà G on XÃÉ permutes these n-cells.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      (Covering Space Existence Thm): For each subgroup H &lt; œÄ1(X,x0), there is a covering space rH: (XÃÉ/H,[xÃÉ0]H) ‚Üí (X,x0) such that rH ‚àò qH = p, where qH: XÃÉ ‚Üí XÃÉ/H is the quotient map, and H = rH‚àó(œÄ1(XÃÉ/H,[xÃÉ0]H)).
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <example>
            <p>
              Examples
            </p>
          </example>

          <corollary xml:id="cor-6.67">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If (X,x0) is a PC, LPC, SLSC space or PC CW complex, H &lt; œÄ1(X,x0), and rH:(XÃÉ/H,[xÃÉ0]H) ‚Üí (X,x0) is the covering space of Thm 6.60(b), then the number of sheets of this covering space is the index of H in œÄ1(X,x0).
              </p>
            </statement>
          </corollary>

        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-build-pres"><title>Building covering spaces for subgroups from group presentations</title>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-6.70">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let \langle A | R \rangle be a presentation of a group G and let X be the presentation complex with vertex x0. Let H &lt; G.
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      (Top-down Method): Let XÃÉ be the Cayley complex of the presentation with quotient map p:XÃÉ ‚Üí X. Then H has a covering space action on XÃÉ, with quotient map qH:XÃÉ ‚Üí XÃÉ/H, and the covering space rH:XÃÉ/H ‚Üí X defined by rH([s]H) := p(s) for all [s]H ‚àà XÃÉ/H satisfies Im rH‚àó = H.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      (Bottom-up Method): Let Z be the CW complex constructed by: Z(0) := H\G (the set of right cosets of H in G). The set of edges of Z is in bijection with H\G √ó A; for each Hg ‚àà H\G and a ‚àà A, the attaching map of the edge eHg,a is œÜHg,a(-1) = Hg and œÜHg,a(1) = Hga. The set of faces of Z is in bijection with H\G √ó R; for each Hg ‚àà H\G and r ‚àà R, the attaching map œÜHg,r of the face fHg,r satisfies œÜHg,r ‚àò œâ := edge path in Z(1) starting at Hg labeled by r. Then r:Z ‚Üí X such that r(Hg) = x0, r(eHg,a) = the edge of X corresponding to a, and r(fHg,r) = the face of X corresponding to r (for all Hg, a, and r) is a covering space and Im r‚àó = H.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

        </subsection>

        <subsection xml:id="subsec-apps"><title>Applications to group theory</title>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-6.75">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Every subgroup of a free group is a free group.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-6.77">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let H be a finite index subgroup of a group G. 
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If G is a finitely generated group, then H is also finitely generated.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If G is a finitely presented group, then H is also finitely presented.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

        </subsection>
        
      </section>

      <section xml:id="sec-galois-cor"><title>The Universal Covering and Galois correspondence</title>

        <definition xml:id="def-6.80">
          <statement>
            <p>
              An isomorphism of pointed covering spaces pi: (Yi,yi) ‚Üí (X,x0) for i=1,2 is a homeomorphism f:(Y1,y1) ‚Üí (Y2,y2) such that p2 ‚àò f = p1.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>

        <theorem xml:id="thm-6.81"><title>Covering Space Uniqueness Theorem</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Any two PC, LPC pointed covering spaces pi: (Yi,yi) ‚Üí (X,x0) (for i=1,2) of a pointed space (X,x0) satisfy p1‚àó(Y1,y1) = p2‚àó(Y2,y2) iff the pointed covering spaces are isomorphic.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </theorem>

        <definition xml:id="def-6.82">
          <statement>
            <p>
