          </theorem>

          <p>
            Motivation: For dimensions n ‚â• 2, the group œÄn(X,x0) is often difficult to compute. Instead, define abelian groups Hn(X) for all n ‚â• 0 that capture much of the same information.
          </p>

          <p>
            Motivation: Define homology groups 3 ways: simplicial homology HnŒî on Œî-complexes, cellular homology HnCW on CW-complexes, and singular homology Hnsing on topological spaces.
            {Œî-complexes} ‚ää {CW complexes} ‚ää {topological spaces}.
            HnŒî is easiest to compute, HnCW is harder to compute but easier to find the complex structure, and Hnsing is hardest to compute but easiest to use for proving theorems.
            For a Œî-complex X, HnŒî(X) = HnCW(X) = Hnsing(X).
